'''Jong Song-ok''' ({{korean|hangul=정성옥|context=north}}; born 18 August 1974) is a female [[long-distance runner]] and [[politician]] from [[North Korea]], who won the world title in the [[1999 World Championships in Athletics - Women's Marathon|women's marathon]] at the [[1999 World Championships in Athletics]] in [[Seville, Spain]]. To date, it is the only medal ever won by a North Korean athlete at the [[World Championships in Athletics|World Championships]].

==Career==
Jong debuted internationally at the [[1995 Military World Games]] where she finished second. She emerged as a new star in a series of North Korean marathoners after having placed third at the [[Beijing Marathon]].{{Sfn|North Korea Handbook|2002|p=493}}

She competed at [[1996 Summer Olympics]] in [[Atlanta]], finishing 20th in the [[Athletics at the 1996 Summer Olympics - Women's marathon|women's marathon]].

In 2000, Jong did not participate in either the [[Boston Marathon]] or the [[2000 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics in Sydney]]; South Korean media claimed this was due to the personal instruction of North Korean leader [[Kim Jong-il]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://article.joins.com/news/article/article.asp?total_id=592158&ctg=00|title=북한 정성옥 보스턴 마라톤 불참|trans-title=North Korea's Jong Song-ok will not join Boston Marathon|work=[[JoongAng Ilbo]]|date=2000-03-29|accessdate=2014-06-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.idomin.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=12967|title=북한 정성옥, 김정일 지시로 올림픽 불참|trans-title=North Korea's Jong Song-ok did not join Sydney Olympics on instructions of Kim Jong-il|work=Domin Ilbo|date=2001-04-21|accessdate=2014-06-30}}</ref> Jong became a delegate to the 10th [[Supreme People's Assembly]] in March 2000.{{Sfn|North Korea Handbook|2002|p=493}}

Jong is the first North Korean sportsperson to have received the title of {{Interlanguage link multi|Hero of the Republic|ko|3=조선민주주의인민공화국의 공화국영웅|lt=Heroine of the Republic}}.{{Sfn|North Korea Handbook|2002|p=493}} She also holds the title of [[People's Athlete]].{{Sfn|North Korea Handbook|2002|p=381}}

==Later life==
Jong married fellow marathon runner [[Kim Jung-won]] in March 2001.{{Sfn|North Korea Handbook|2002|p=492}} During the [[2008 Olympic torch relay]] in [[Pyongyang]], she was the last person to carry the Olympic torch through the streets.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pyongyang Torch Relay Passes Without Hitch|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2008/04/29/2008042961008.html|publisher=Chosun Ilbo|accessdate=6 December 2012|date=April 29, 2008 <!-- at 07:52 KST --> }}</ref>

